== 2...c5 · Steinitz countergambit ==

Black challenges the centre with c5, the Steinitz countergambit,<ref>So called, but since White didn't offer a gambit previously, shouldn't it be called the Steinitz '''gambit'''?</ref> offering White their c-pawn. 

=== Decline the gambit ===

As the pawn is already defended by the Queen, White does not actually ''need'' to defend it further: if 3. Nc3 cxd4 4. Qxd4 and White is threatening to win Black's d-pawn: 4...Nc6? 5. Qxd5 Qxd5 6. Nxd5{{Chess/not|++}} (if 4...e6 5. Bxb8! Rxb8 and White's centralised queen is unassailable). 

Usually however White ''does'' end up over-defending the d-pawn, because most of the moves they'd like to play next happen to do so anyway. White usually plays [[/3. e3|'''3. e3''']], which defends d4 but is also essential for opening up White's kings-side bishop. After 3...Nf6, Black has transposed back into [[Chess Opening Theory/1. d4/1...Nf6/2. Bf4/2...d5/3. e3/3...c5|the main line against the Accelerated London]].

Other London system-moves '''3. c3''' or '''3. Nf3''' may be played and usually transpose. 

=== Accept the gambit ===

{{Chess/board|moves=1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 c5 3. dxc5 Nc6 4. Nf3 f6 5. e3 e5 6. Bg3 Bxc5|caption=Mason v. Steinitz (1883). Position after turn 6. Accepting the countergambit allows Black to take over the centre and get a comfortable position.|frame=1|float=left}}

Accepting the gambit, '''3. dxc5?!''', is unwise. By taking the pawn, White reduces their control over the centre and Black can easily recover the pawn. [[wikipedia:James Mason (chess player)|Mason]], pioneer of the London system, fell into this in his game against [[wikipedia:Wilhelm Steinitz|Steinitz]] in 1883.<ref name="mason">[https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1002036 Mason v Steinitz 1883 - Chessgames.com]</ref> It continued like this: 3. dxc5?! Nc6 4. Nf3 f6 5. e3 e5 6. Bg3 Bxc5 (see diagram).

=== Countergambit ===

A rare sideline here is the '''Morris countergambit'''<ref>For whatever reason not called the Morris '''Counter-'''countergambit.</ref>, '''3. e4'''. White gives up their e-pawn in order to push d5 and cramp Black's position. This resembles an [[Chess Opening Theory/1. d4/1...d5/2. c4/2...e5|Albin Countergambit]] with colours reversed. 

